{"Body":"<p><em><strong><a href=\"http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/oestrus#Etymology\" rel=\"nofollow\">oestrus</a></em></strong></p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>From the Latin <strong>oestrus</strong> (\"gadfly”, “sting”, “frenzy\"), from the Ancient Greek <strong>οἶστρος</strong> (oistros).</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p><em><strong><a href=\"http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/hiero-#Etymology\" rel=\"nofollow\">hiero-</a></em></strong></p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>From Ancient Greek prefix <strong>ἱερo-</strong> (<strong>hiero-</strong>), from <strong>ἱερός</strong> (<strong>hieros</strong>, \"sacred, holy\")</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p><strong><a href=\"http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E1%BC%B1%CE%B5%CF%81%CF%8C%CF%82#Ancient_Greek\" rel=\"nofollow\">ἱερός</a></strong></p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>From Proto-Indo-European <strong>*ish₂ros</strong>. There are a number of candidate cognates with this word. \n  Compare Sanskrit इषिर (iṣirá) and Oscan  (aisusis).</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>Both the two words derive from the same PIE noun *ish₂ros, but why did the Ancient Greek decendants own different meanings with a prefixed \"h\" from each other, further giving \"hiero-\" and \"oestrus\"?</p>\n", "Id":"3389", "LastEditorUserId":"1306", "Title":"How does Gk. \"hieros\" differ from its cognate Gk. \"oistros\" with an \"h\"?", "CreationDate":"2013-03-16T15:39:19.320", "OwnerUserId":"1306", "PostTypeId":"1", "Tags":"<etymology><sound-change>", "AnswerCount":"2", "comments":[], "LastEditDate":"2013-03-17T02:17:05.077", "LastEditedUser":{"UpVotes":"13", "WebsiteUrl":"", "DownVotes":"0", "Id":"1306", "AccountId":"1783961", "Views":"2", "Reputation":"515", "CreationDate":"2012-09-03T14:12:48.473", "DisplayName":"archenoo", "LastAccessDate":"2014-01-16T14:31:46.963", "AboutMe":"<p>A linguistic amateur</p>\n", "Age":"25"}, "ViewCount":"106", "LastActivityDate":"2013-03-17T02:17:05.077", "Score":"1", "CommentCount":"1", "OwnerUser":{"UpVotes":"13", "WebsiteUrl":"", "DownVotes":"0", "Id":"1306", "AccountId":